</center></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/ubalanzsonofanz.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Balanz son of Anz</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Abuser of EZCodes</span><br>  Posts: 2052<br> <font color=#333333>(10/6/02 2:09:14 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerfrm32.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=353.topic&index=29>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: '/drop' command needed badly by mages</span><hr size=1> As much as I want a <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> /drop</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> command and auto drop for summoned duplicate lore, I think the main effect would be to unmask what I think is the most glaring problem for the mage class, which I call <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> The Wizard-Rod Problem.</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
Basically, the problem is this.  Since Wizard nukes are currently in all ways superior to mage nukes, is there any reason, other than courtesy and fun, not to give rods to Wizards instead of nuking ourselves?  If this is the case, and since pets require little or no mana to maintain, and debuffs are done at the beginning of a fight, it means that under many circumstances the only rational strategy for mages on raids is to make rods.  It is not simply a matter of Wizards being greedy, but it being rational.<br>
<br>
The only limiting factors appear to be time and aggro.  I am working on a model, but my preliminary results indicate that under most raid circumstances, that it is easy and probably common for all the capacity of mana producers <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> (mages)</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> to be used by mana consumers <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> (priests and wizards)</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.<br>
<br>
I understand the argument that massive rod production is only really required in a small number of encounters, but my experience and my models suggest that this is only really true for strong guilds with sufficient numbers of all classes to draw upon appropriate for the encounter.  If either the mix of caster classes is inadequate, or the raid is pushing the limit of their capability, it is easy for mana demand to consume maximum mana supply.<br>
<br>
I will present my model later, after I clean it up a bit.<br>
<br>
This might not be the case, there might not really be a problem.  But enough mages report dissatisfaction with being reduced to rod machines that it is worth investigating, and I suspect the model will support these complaints.<br>
<br>
If it is so, it is a major flaw for endgame mages, and in my mind, the worst problem that we face.<br>
<br>
Only one solution occurs to me yet, but it is fairly radical, and I want to line my ducks all up in row before I propose it.  However, some will be glad to know that will involve restoring our status as the second best nukers, although not in the most obvious way.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Raz</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
